C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                              FY 2024      FY 2025     FY 2026
Title: Defensive Cyberspace Operations - Space (DCO-S)                                                                              73.364      104.088     102.439
Description: Funding supports cyber hardening DCO-S activities for the space enterprise. Provides space enterprise defensive
cyber solutions to counter advanced persistence cyber threats, through rapid fielding of operational prototypes using agile
development methods.

FY 2025 Plans:

Operational Systems Development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024   FY 2025       FY 2026
Expand deployment, development, tuning, and rapid prototype capabilities of DCO-S and field to 23 mission area locations (11
Manticore and 12 Kraken product lines) based on operational/user priorities; build, test, and deliver features at a faster pace to
meet growing demands of cyber defenders. Scale development and deployment teams to increase emphasis on cyber threat
recognition, information sharing, and active response methodologies to combat evolving threats and prepare for inevitable
changes to the cyber domain. Augment platform, Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment (CI/CD), and test teams to
provision, manage, optimize, and secure infrastructure on premise, begin development of cloud hosting environments, carry out
software deployments, and validate the reliability of DCO-S features. Upgrade DCO-S databases, grow infrastructure support of
existing codebase. Integrate and deploy required software changes mandated from commercial product suppliers due to baseline
changes to functionality, end of manufacturing, end of support, or other necessary system changes. Standing up a service-wide
help desk to support deployed locations and users of DCO-S.

Transition from SWP Planning Phase into SWP Execution Phase, document and independently verify the DCO-S Minimum
Viable Product (MVP) as required in SWP, to be tested and operationally accepted in FY 2026. Increase Systems Engineering
& Integration (SE&I) support to ensure seamless data stream integration with each new on-boarded mission system. Through
AFRL Cyber Research & Development, increase efforts to develop technical documentation, perform integration activities and
tuning support, and develop initial plans for product support and sustainment. Increase overall deployment activities to on-board
these additional mission systems, and emerging deployment requirements, at a faster pace to ensure all systems are protected
sooner. Additional efforts will focus on implementing machine learning (ML) to increase the speed of threat detection and reduce
the overall reaction time for defense of mission systems and identify and deliver automated testing.

DCO-S software development efforts during the SWP Planning Phase have resulted in significant accomplishments to include
12 Agile Epics, 44 Features, 321 Stories, and 169 Tests currently underway. We have successfully delivered advanced threat
detection systems, automated incident response, enhanced network security monitoring, and are planning to further enhance
these on premises capabilities via cloud deployment to bring these capabilities to many users.

Establish baseline for global space cybersecurity competition to help reduce vulnerabilities within existing product lines. Fund
efforts to allow independent security researchers to report security exploits, issues, and hardware flaws which increases the
chances that bugs are found and reported before malicious attacks occur. Leverage other agencies' lessons learned and
capability as it pertains to defending space systems and expand capability to defending space systems.

Expand systems engineering, development infrastructure, and accreditation support to provide internal test and accreditation
plans for security hardening and risk assessments to ensure product line software has optimum security features,
countermeasures, and safeguards in place when operationally tested in FY 2026. Maintain modern testing methodologies based
on industry best practices; embed the 47th Test Squadron into the development workflow, toolchain and CI/CD framework and

Operational Systems Development

