first, modular approach allows for distributed construction across the industrial base, with U.S. shipyards focusing on final assembly and integration. The strategy is
designed to stabilize the workforce, increase industrial resilience, and deliver the new capability more predictably and affordably.

FY27 funding supports risk reduction through system-level integration, collaborative efforts with the shipbuilder and stakeholders, land-based and ship-based test
planning, and land based testing facility standup.

This Project Unit includes the development and risk reduction of BBG(X) advanced surface ship Hull, Mechanical, and Electrical (HM&E) components and systems.
The BBG(X) power and propulsion risk mitigation demonstration sub-project will be used to de-risk the BBG(X) Integrated Power System (IPS). The BBG(X) hardware
development and procurement and land-based testing efforts executed under this PE are informed by BBG(X) Ship Design specifications developed under PE
0603564N / PU 0413. IPS test findings will inform decisions in baseline specifications and design products, developed under PE 0603564N / PU 0413, ensuring that the
ship can accommodate the space, weight, power, cooling (SWAP-C) required by the IPS and that the IPS can meet BBG(X) power and energy requirements.

The Battleship power and energy requirements are needed both for propulsion and ship service mission loads. The 30 knots sustained speed requirement of the
Battleship will drive large propulsion power requirements. The large sensors and directed energy weapons required on Battleship at delivery or planned for future
upgrade will drive mission loads. These two types of power and energy requirements necessitate the need for a robust power and propulsion design and risk reduction
effort.

The interdependency of BBG(X) design and IPS risk reduction is critical. This project will employ a four-phased testing and risk reduction approach to build assurance
that the BBG(X) IPS system can be installed and activated efficiently by the shipbuilder with performance characteristics that are well understood.
-Phase 1 (IPS Modeling & Simulation (M&S)), commenced in FY 2021, establishes a description of the components and system non-real-time models that are needed
for the DDG(X) IPS digital engineering effort to provide performance feedback to BBG(X) IPS design and specification. Persistent digital engineering efforts initiated as
part of Phase 1 extend through the life of the BBG(X) program.
-Phase 2 (Land based testing) commenced in FY 2021, under the DDG(X) program and transferred to BBG(X), initially employs refined digital models and scaled
integrated surrogate components that functionally represent the intended BBG(X) IPS and transitions to full scale testing by procurement, integration and test of BBG(X)
specific major long lead hardware components.
-Phase 3 (Land Based Engineering Site (LBES)) builds a tactical representation of the BBG(X) shipboard power and propulsion system based on the BBG(X) full scale
hardware procured in phase 2. The LBES will be an enduring activity over the life of the ship and provides capability to perform performance & endurance testing of the
IPS.
-Phase 4 (Shipboard Test & Activation), funded by future BBG(X) Shipbuilding and Conversion, Navy (SCN), conducts shipboard integration testing of the power and
propulsion system with other ship systems to confirm performance as specified in the contract requirements and interoperability at the platform level.

