 Strike Command transitions to a Joint Fires Network with redundant and alternative data networks, the B-2 must update BLOS capabilities in kind to support Command
 and Control, Joint Fires Integration, and mission execution. Securing this alternate network connectivity will ensure long-range integration capability and increase combat
 effectiveness through a modern, resilient, and reliable construct.

B-2 Digital High Frequency (HF) program provides a terrestrial-based resilient and reliable alternative Beyond Line of Sight (BLOS) communication capability in Highly
Contested Environments (HCE). This communications pathway does not require satellite constellation networks to work. This capability will increase the B-2 warfighters
ability to operate and communicate in HCE which is necessary for high-end operations and provides Combatant Commanders increased command and control flexibility.
Funding will enable the rapid integration and fielding of the HF Argus System onto the federated Adaptable Communication Suite (ACS) as a roll on/off capability.
Also, the system is designed to receive advanced HF waveforms for tasking and targeting and demonstrates long range communications. Funds are required for B-2
integration to include lab test, hardware, certification, flight test, and associated supporting activities.

The B-2 Spirit's AN/APQ-181 radar is essential for its penetrating strike mission. However, the radar's "backend" components are obsolete, unreliable, and
unsustainable, driving radar failures and impacting aircraft availability. This Radar Modernization RDT&E program addresses these critical deficiencies by developing
and testing a modernization solution. The core of this effort is to design, fabricate, and qualify a Signal Translation Unit (STU). This STU will serve as the critical
interface between the B-2's existing Active Electronically Scanned Array (AESA) antenna and modernized, backend processors. RDT&E funds will be used for systems
engineering, STU development and associated LRUs, antenna integration, and extensive integration testing in a lab environment to prove the viability of the hybrid
architecture. This effort will mature the design and mitigate technical risk, ensuring the solution is ready for subsequent procurement and fleet-wide fielding. This
program is essential to develop a producible and effective solution to the B-2's most pressing radar sustainability issue.

Flight Test (Baseline Support) maintains and upgrades the B-2 unique flight test aircraft as well as hardware/software and instrumentation and test equipment to support
developmental and operational systems integration and flight test.

Flight Test (Baseline Support) also provides for other B-2 unique government costs and includes assorted studies of aircraft performance as well as acquisition planning
activities, up to and including proposal preparation, engine, weapon, communication, navigation or other capabilities, including range support.

B-2 funding may be used to resolve emerging safety of flight and diminishing manufacturing sources issues, and fulfill FAA or other mandates necessary to ensure
continued aircrew safety and mission effectiveness. Funding may also support innovation activities including, but not limited to, studies, analyses, requirements
definition, and quick-reaction capability prototypes/demonstrations to accelerate planning for technology transition, technology insertion, and future acquisition programs.

